    <remark>
      Notice that in <xref ref="distinguish-between-max-and-min"/>, there are two ways we talk about max and min. We might want to know the location of where the max or min are (i.e., determining at which <m>x</m>-value the max or min occurs at) or we might want to know what the max or min are (i.e., the <m>y</m>-value). 
      <p> Also, note that in <xref ref="distinguish-between-max-and-min"/>, a local minimum is also a global minimum.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <activity xml:id="find-all-characteristics">
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Use the following graph to answer the questions below.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="graph-with-all-characteristics">
            <image>
            <sageplot>
              p=line([(-8,4),(-2,4)],thickness=3, gridlines=[[-8..11],[-8..11]])
              p+=plot(spline([(-2,4.1),(-0.5,8),(2,-3),(4.9,9.4)]),(x,-2,5),thickness=3)
              p+=arrow((4.9,9.4),(5,10),thickness=3)
              p+=point((-8,4),pointsize=50,color='blue',xmin=-9,xmax=6,ymin=-5,ymax=10)
              p
            </sageplot>
          </image>
        </figure>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the domain?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <m>[-8,\infty)</m>
          </p>
        </answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            What is the range?
          </p>
        </statement>
